  <p>The point of the table isn't to make it a race. It's that 118 commits/day sounds superhuman until you see the inputs &mdash; more concurrent agents, more hours, no kids. The workflow itself isn't magic. It's accessible to anyone willing to learn it.</p>

  <h2>Who can do this</h2>

  <p>I think the reason there aren't more people doing this is that it requires an unusual intersection:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Senior engineering skills</strong> &mdash; you need enough experience to architect systems and review AI output critically</li>
    <li><strong>Financial runway</strong> &mdash; this doesn't pay (yet) while you're building</li>
    <li><strong>Free time</strong> &mdash; or at least, fragmented time you can fill with short agent sessions</li>
    <li><strong>Genuine obsession</strong> &mdash; I basically do nothing else besides code and spend time with my family</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Most developers have one or two of these, not all four.</p>

